Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.
result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Josey M Grill

records.addlTxt:
(1:32 PM cases 22CF420, 22CF1034 called.) All parties and court personnel appear via Zoom. 
Defendant Josey M Grill appeared by video, in custody in the Chippewa County Jail. Attorney Zebulon Patek in court for Josey M Grill. Prosecuting attorney Andrew James Gunderson in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Defendant waives right to appear in person and wants to proceed. Court accepts the defendant's waiver to appear in person.
Defendant waives right to a preliminary hearing in cases 22CF420, 22CF1034 and Court accepts waivers.
Attorney Patek to schedule an Arraignment in both cases with Branch 1 Judicial Assistant.
Preliminary hearing on September 27, 2022 at 01:30 pm.

8:30 AM cases 19CF512 and 22CF420 called. Defendant Josey M Grill not in court and does not appear via Zoom.  Attorney Zebulon Patek in court for Josey M Grill.  Attorney Peter J. Rindal in court for State of Wisconsin. 
The defense has no information as to the missed appearance. State requests a warrant- So ordered.
8:32 AM cases re called. Defendant Josey M Grill in court.  Attorney Zebulon Patek in court for Josey M Grill.  Attorney Peter J. Rindal in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Warrants are quashed. State asks court to vacate the DAGP in 19CF512 with argument citing new criminal charges in Chippewa, Dunn and Eau Claire counties. 
Defense asks court to extend DAGP agreement. State objects and renews their request to vacate the agreement between the State and Defense. 
Court vacates the DAGP and finds defendant Guilty on counts 1 and 3 in 19CF512. 
State and Defense make sentencing recommendations. 
Court orders 2 years Probation with conditions: 
Complete AODA and follow through with recommendations. 
Maintain absolute sobriety. Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge. 
Any conditions, programming or treatment per the agent and follow through with recommendations. 
No contact with any known drug dealers/users except in a therapeutic setting. 
No entry to bars, liquor stores or taverns. 
No Contact with Officer A.B. except in his official capacity. 
Defendant to pay court costs including DNA sample surcharge and a $100 paper service fee. 
On count 3 only: 120 days in Jail all but 20 days Stayed. The imposed 20 days can be completed by 160 hours of community service. 
Defendant chooses to complete the community service. 
Probation can end after 18 months if the PO thinks it is appropriate. PO to submit a letter to the DA's office. 

In 22CF420: A preliminary hearing is scheduled for 9/27/2022 at 1:30 PM.

10:28 AM Prosecuting attorney Matthew Z Kirkpatrick in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Josey M Grill in court.  Attorney Zebulon Patek in court for Josey M Grill.
Hearing scheduled for July 14, 2022 at 09:30 am.
